That—


(1) Section 22 of the Finance Act 1977 (alteration of personal reliefs) shall have effect, and be deemed always to have had effect, as if—


(a) in paragraph (a) of subsection (1) (increase of married allowance to £1,295) for ' £1,295 ' there were substituted £1,455 ' ;

(b) in paragraph (b) of that subsection (increase of single allowance and wife's earned income relief to £845) for '£845' there were substituted ' £945' ;

(c) in paragraph (c) of that subsection (increase of age allowance to £1,765 and £1,120) for ' £1,765' and £1,120' there were substituted £1,975 ' and £1,250' ;

(d) in subsection (3) (increase of additional allowance to £450) for £450' there were substituted £510'. 


(2) The above amendments shall not apply for the purposes of subsection (2) and the corresponding provision in subsection (3) of the said section 22.

But this Resolution shall not require any change to be made in the amounts deductible or repayable under section 204 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1970 (pay as you earn) before 6th December 1977.

And it is hereby declared that it is expedient in the public interest that this Resolution should have statutory effect under the provisions of the Provisional Collection of Taxes Act 1968.

That, for the purposes of any Act of the present Session to make provision for lump sum payments to pensioners, it is expedient to authorise the payment out of moneys provided by Parliament of


(a) any sums required for making payments under that Act by virtue of qualifying benefits entitlement to which arises or is treated as arising under any enactment or instrument applying in the United Kingdom generally or in Great Britain only, being payments not exceeding the following amount in the case of any person, that is to say £10 together with a further £10 in respect of any spouse of that person ;

(b) any administrative costs incurred by any government department (including a Northern Ireland department) in connection with the making of any such payments.—[Mr. Robert Sheldon.]
